2)  Research that was conducted 

To enhance this project, I conducted research on strategies for building smaller and efficient Docker container images. The technique that is often suggested for accomplishing this objective involves the concept of multi-stage Docker builds. Traditional Docker build strategies involve including all build dependencies within a single image, resulting in a larger image. With the implementation of multi-stage Docker build strategy, the application code and dependencies are the only elements that will be included in the image. 

3) Improvements that were made 

For Task 2, it was necessary to use Docker for packaging the data processing application in Python. At first, the Dockerfile used only one-stage building using python:3.9-slim image. It was suggested that in order to optimize the process, the use of multistage Docker building should be implemented. In the proposed technique, dependencies are installed at the building stage, and the needed application is placed in the runtime stage only. 

 4)The impacts and the benefits  

 

Smaller images sizes: As a result of having only necessary runtime components in the image, multi-stage builds create smaller images compared to the images created using single-stage builds. Smaller images mean faster image downloads, lower storage capacity needed, and faster container startup. 

Enhanced security: The final image becomes safer as there is no need to add all the build tools and dependencies that are not required after building the application to the final image. 

Maintainability: By separating the build process and runtime process in your application, you can easily modify or update one of them without affecting the other part. This allows easier maintenance of the image. 

Improved build speed: By creating smaller images and making better use of Docker's build cache, the process becomes faster since you do not have to build layers that already exist from previous images if the build dependencies or code remains the same. 

Parallel builds: The process of building an image in multi-stage builds allows parallelizing the build process. 

Reference -  Jayaprakash, A. (2024, September 12). Understanding multi-stage Docker builds. Blacksmith. https://www.blacksmith.sh/blog/understanding-multi-stage-docker-builds  

 

